05143nam a22007095i 9781646022045DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1399980296  a97816460220457 a10.1515/97816460220452doi  a(DE-B1597)651542  a(OCoLC)1380734764  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a933/.01qOCoLC223/eng/202308041 aBechar, Shlomit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Change and Material Culture in Middle to Late Bronze Age Canaan /cShlomit Bechar. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory, Archaeology, and Culture of the Levant00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. The Transition from the Middle to the Late Bronze Age: Architectural Aspects at Hazor -- tChapter 3. The Middle Bronze Age–Late Bronze Age Transition in the Levant: Architectural Aspects -- tChapter 4. Pottery Assemblages from the Middle and Late Bronze Ages -- tChapter 5. Discussion and Conclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo shifts in material culture instigate administrative change, or is it the shifting political winds that affect material culture? This is the central question that Shlomit Bechar addresses in this book, taking the transition from the Middle to Late Bronze Age (seventeenth–fourteenth centuries BCE) in northern Canaan as a test case.Combining archaeological and historical analysis, Bechar identifies the most significant changes evident in architectural and ceramic remains from this period and then explores how and why contemporary political shifts may have influenced, or been influenced by, these developments. Bechar persuasively argues that the Egyptian conquest of the southern Levant—enabled by local economic decline following the expulsion of the Hyksos and the fall of northern Syrian cities—was the impetus for these changes in ceramics and architecture. Using a macro-typological approach to examine the ceramic assemblages, she also discusses the impact of the influx of Aegean imports, suggesting that while “attached specialists” were primarily responsible for ceramic production in the Middle Bronze Age, Late Bronze Age ceramics were increasingly made by “independent specialists,” another important result of the new administrative system created following Thutmose III’s campaign.An important contribution to our understanding of the transition between the Middle and Late Bronze Ages, this original and insightful book will appeal to specialists in the Bronze Age Levant, especially those interested in using ceramic assemblages to examine social and political change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPalestine-History-To 70 A.D. 0aPottery, Ancient. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aEgypt.  aLate Bronze Age.  aLevant.  aMaterial Culture.  aMiddle Bronze Age.  aPolitical changes.  aPottery analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022 Englishz978311099291508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022z9783110992878oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781646022045?locatt=mode:leg